<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>Astronomy data needs to be calibrated for the transmission of the atmosphere and for the response of the instruments.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>As a result, data in astronomy stays "live" much longer than in other disciplines -- it needs an active "curation," mostly by the expert group that collected the data.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>With each new understanding of how corrections should be made, the data are reprocessed and recalibrated.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>And in the expanding Universe, the light emitted by distant objects is redshifted.</a>
